tudents. In this book, Perry L. Glanzer, Jonathan P. Hill, and Byron R. Johnson explore college students' search for meaning and purpose and the role that higher education plays. To shed empirical light on this complex issue, the authors draw on in-depth interviews with four hundred college students from different types of institutions across the United States. They also analyze three sets of national survey data: the National Study of Youth and Religion, College Students Beliefs and Values, and their own Gallup-conducted survey of 2,500 college students. Their research identifies important social, educational, and cultural influences that shape students' quests and the answers they find. Arguing against a utilitarian view of education, Glanzer, Hill, and Johnson conclude that colleges and universities can and should cultivate and aid students in their journeys, and they offer suggestions for doing so.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristian educationzUnited States. 0aChristian universities and collegeszUnited States. 0aCollege studentsxConduct of life. 0aCollege studentsxReligious lifezUnited States. 0aCollege studentszUnited StatesvInterviews. 0aCollege studentszUnited StatesxInterviews. 0aEducation, HigherxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSelf-actualization (Psychology)xReligious aspects. 0aStudentsxConduct of life. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aEducation : Philosophy of Education. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aHill, Jonathan P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJohnson, Byron R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://doi.org/10